she
asked
for a candle, and would have
retired to her chamber; but Mrs.
Webster
had
prepared
some
little delicacy for her
supper
, and
she
had
too much good-nature and
politeness
to
refuse
sitting
up to partake of it.
The
curiosity
of Spriggins and the two elder
Websters
was excited by the behaviour of Hamden
Auberry
.
They had talked it over as they walked home
together
,
and all agreed that he was certainly a lover.
The company he was with declared he was of a
superior
rank in life; but they had not been quite
pleased
that our heroine had neglected to introduce them.
He is a
monstrous
handsome
man,
said
Belle, the
second
