that elegance.
In
short
, Rachel was the kind of woman who gives
taste
and
fashion
to every thing
she
wears, however
plain its formation, however common the materials of
which it is made.
The
state
of her mind, after the departure of her
husband
was
such
, as precluded every idea of
seeking
society
during the day. She attempted, but the
attempt
was vain, to partake of a meal which the care
of Lettuce had provided (for Lettuce had performed
the office of attendant on the
person
of our heroine
from the
